goals.question: What is the correlation between fertility and life expectancy?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of fertility vs life_expect
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is any relationship between fertility and life expectancy. If there is a negative correlation, it could indicate that countries with higher fertility rates have lower life expectancies.

goals.question: What is the distribution of fertility across countries?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of fertility rates across different countries. It could help us identify countries with high or low fertility rates.

goals.question: What is the distribution of life expectancy across countries?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of life expectancies across different countries. It could help us identify countries with high or low life expectancies.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y', errors='coerce')
    plt.scatter(data['fertility'], data['life_expect'])
    plt.title('What is the correlation between fertility and life expectancy?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Fertility')
    plt.ylabel('Life Expectancy')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data = data.dropna(subset=['fertility'])
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax.hist(data['fertility'], bins=20, color='blue', alpha=0.5)
    ax.axvline(data['fertility'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Mean: {data['fertility'].mean():.2f}")
    ax.axvline(data['fertility'].median(), color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Median: {data['fertility'].median():.2f}")
    ax.set_xlabel('Fertility')
    ax.set_ylabel('Frequency')
    ax.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of fertility across countries?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data = data.dropna(subset=['life_expect'])
    plt.hist(data['life_expect'], bins=20, color='green')
    plt.axvline(data['life_expect'].median(), color='red', label='Median: {:.2f}'.format(data['life_expect'].median()))
    plt.xlabel('Life Expectancy')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of life expectancy across countries?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.scatter(data['n_fertility'], data['n_life_expect'])
    ax.set_xlabel('Normalized Fertility')
    ax.set_ylabel('Normalized Life Expectancy')
    ax.set_title('What is the relationship between normalized fertility and normalized life expectancy?')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['n_fertility'].plot(kind='hist', bins=20, color='green', alpha=0.5)
    plt.axvline(data['n_fertility'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Median: {:.2f}'.format(data['n_fertility'].median()))
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of normalized fertility across countries?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
